<h3 class="sub-head">Colombia: The Reliable Benchmark</h3>

<p class="body">Colombia has a structural advantage no other origin shares: two harvest seasons per year, a main harvest (October through February) and a secondary fly crop (April through June). This means fresh Colombian coffee is almost always available somewhere in a specialty roaster's catalog, making it the most practical origin for a house coffee that needs year-round consistency.</p>

<p class="body">The most prized Colombian regions are Huila, Nariño, and Cauca in the southern highlands. Huila coffees are the standard for what specialty people mean when they say "clean and sweet": balanced acidity, caramel, stone fruit, red apple, mild enough that people who think they do not like "acidic" coffee often enjoy it. Nariño sits at some of the highest elevations in Colombia and produces coffees with more brightness, more tropical fruit, and a sparkling acidity that challenges Kenyan lots. Cauca sits between the two in character.</p>

<p class="body">Colombia is the safest first single-origin recommendation for someone transitioning from grocery-store blends. The coffees are approachable, well-documented, and consistently good across a wide range of roasters.</p>

<h3 class="sub-head">Kenya: Intensity and Acidity</h3>

<p class="body">Kenyan coffee has a reputation for being the most intense single-origin experience in the specialty world. This reputation is earned. The SL28 and SL34 varieties, developed by Scott Agricultural Laboratories in the colonial era specifically for Kenyan growing conditions, produce cups with a blackcurrant-like acidity, full body, and a tomato-like savory quality that reads almost like wine at high quality levels. This is not for everyone, but for the people it is for, no other origin compares.</p>

<p class="body">The Kenyan grading system (AA, AB, PB for Peaberry) refers primarily to bean size. AA is the largest screen size (17-18) and commands the highest prices, though the correlation between screen size and cup quality is imperfect. The most important variable in Kenyan quality is the washing station and the producer cooperative behind it.</p>

<p class="body">Kenya works best roasted light to medium, where the blackcurrant and citrus brightness is preserved. Dark-roast Kenyan is technically possible but loses the distinctive character that justifies the price premium. If you are going to spend money on Kenyan, roast it in a range where the investment shows up in the cup.</p>

<h3 class="sub-head">Sumatra: The Full-Body Exception</h3>

<p class="body">Sumatra occupies a category of its own in specialty coffee partly because of its flavor profile and partly because of the processing method almost unique to Indonesia: wet-hulled, or Giling Basah. In standard washed processing, coffee dries in its parchment until it reaches low moisture content before hulling. In wet-hulling, the parchment is removed while the coffee still has relatively high moisture content, and then the naked bean continues to dry without its protective layer.</p>

<p class="body">The result is a visually distinctive bean (irregular, dark blue-green before roasting) and a distinctive cup: earthy, herbal, full-bodied, low-acid, with notes that range from dark chocolate and tobacco to forest floor and cedar. It is one of the few origins that improves as roast level increases toward medium-dark, because the processing has already built in body and earthiness that benefits from the deeper roast development. This makes Sumatran coffee excellent for espresso, milk-based drinks, and customers who find lighter-roasted single origins too delicate or acidic.</p>

