<h3 class="sub-head">Costa Rica: The Honey Pioneer</h3>

<p class="body">Costa Rica's most important contribution to specialty coffee may not be a flavor profile but a processing innovation. Honey processing, which involves removing the cherry skin while leaving varying amounts of the sticky mucilage on the bean during drying, was pioneered and refined by Costa Rican micro-mills in the early 2000s. Carlos Ureña of Hacienda Sonora and other producers in the Central Valley developed the yellow, red, and black honey classifications that are now used globally.</p>

<p class="body">Tarrazu is the most acclaimed Costa Rican region, producing coffees with bright citric acidity, clean stone fruit, and exceptional clarity when washed. The same region's honey-processed lots shift toward peach, apricot, and tropical sweetness with a fuller body and slightly less acidity. For a single-origin buyer who wants to understand what processing method does to a coffee, buying the same Costa Rican origin in washed and honey versions side by side is one of the most educational purchases possible.</p>

