<h3 class="sub-head">Brazil: The World's Baseline</h3>

<p class="body">Brazil produces roughly one-third of the world's coffee supply. This scale means the country's coffees anchor the commodity market but also, increasingly, compete in the specialty tier. Brazil's geography sets it apart from every other major producer: most of the country's coffee-growing regions are at relatively low altitudes (800 to 1,200 MASL) and flat enough for mechanical harvesting. This changes everything about the cup profile.</p>

<p class="body">Low altitude, mechanical harvesting, and the natural and pulped-natural processing methods common in Brazil produce coffees with heavy body, low acidity, and flavors that skew toward dark chocolate, hazelnut, walnut, and mild fruit. These are not the most exciting single-origin cups in the specialty world, but they are often the most approachable and the most practical for espresso. Brazil is the reason so many roasters' signature espresso blends are based on a Brazilian component: the body, sweetness, and muted acidity hold up under high pressure and pair effortlessly with milk.</p>

<p class="body">Sul de Minas, Cerrado Mineiro, and Matas de Minas are the leading specialty regions. The difference between these regions is subtle for most drinkers: Sul de Minas tends slightly fruitier, Cerrado is more consistent and uniform, and Matas de Minas produces some of the most complexity-forward naturals in the country. For the single-origin buyer, Brazil is worth trying as an espresso or a base for a homemade blend, even if it is rarely the most thrilling pour-over in the lineup.</p>

<h2 class="section-head">Single Origin vs Blends: <em>The Honest Comparison</em></h2>

<p class="body">The specialty industry's early years were defined in part by a push toward single origins as the antidote to the dishonest opacity of commodity blends. That context has softened. Experienced roasters now treat single origins and blends as different tools for different purposes rather than competing quality tiers.</p>

<p class="body">Single origins are better at: expressing terroir, communicating a specific farm or producer's work, showcasing seasonal flavors, serving the pour-over customer who wants to taste one clearly defined thing, and giving a roastery's menu a sense of discovery and rotation. They are also more variable. A great Ethiopian washed from last year's harvest may cup differently than this year's harvest from the same farm, and that is not a defect. It is seasonality, which some customers love and others find frustrating.</p>

<p class="body">Blends are better at: consistency across the entire year, building specific flavor targets (a round espresso with reliable crema, a balanced house drip with no surprises), buffering against one origin having a difficult year, and serving a wholesale customer who needs the same cup profile in January and July. A well-built house blend is one of the hardest things a roaster does because it requires balancing multiple variables from multiple origins to land on a repeatable target. When a blend is done well, it is a real creative achievement, not a lesser product.</p>

<p class="body">The practical rule: for filter brewing, start with single origins. For espresso, both are excellent choices, and the best version for you depends on whether you want repeatability (blend) or discovery (single origin). For wholesale accounts serving high-volume drip coffee, blends are usually the right recommendation.</p>

<h2 class="section-head">How to Read <em>a Coffee Bag</em></h2>

<p class="body">A specialty coffee bag communicates a lot of information if you know what to look for. Here is what each label element means in practice.</p>

<p class="body"><strong>Roast Date, Not Best By Date:</strong> The most important date on the bag is the roast date. Coffee is at its best in the two to four weeks after roasting, as CO2 outgassing slows and the aromatics stabilize. "Best by" dates are largely meaningless because coffee does not spoil in the conventional sense, it just becomes stale. Any specialty roaster worth buying from puts the roast date on the bag. If the bag only has a best-by date, the roaster is hiding when it was roasted.</p>

<p class="body"><strong>Processing Method:</strong> Washed, natural, honey, anaerobic, or wet-hulled. This single label is one of the biggest predictors of cup character. Washed coffees cup clean, terroir-forward, and bright. Naturals cup fruity, full-bodied, and sometimes funky. Honeys fall between. Anaerobic processing produces unusual and sometimes polarizing flavors. Understanding processing is what lets you predict a cup's character before you taste it.</p>

<p class="body"><strong>Variety:</strong> Bourbon, Geisha, SL28, Typica, Catuai, and hundreds of others. The variety matters less to most consumers than the origin and process, but for enthusiasts it is meaningful. Geisha is the most famous high-value variety. Bourbon-lineage varieties (Caturra, Catuai, Villa Sarchi, Pacas) are common across Central America. Heirloom Ethiopian varieties are often simply labeled "Ethiopian landrace" because the genetic complexity of wild Ethiopian coffee resists neat categorization.</p>

<p class="body"><strong>Altitude:</strong> Often listed as MASL (meters above sea level). Higher is generally better for arabica because cooler temperatures slow cherry development and produce more complex flavors. Below 1,000 MASL is the threshold for commodity arabica. 1,500 to 2,000 MASL is the sweet spot for most high-quality specialty origins. Above 2,000 MASL is exceptional altitude that commands a premium.</p>

<p class="body"><strong>Certifications:</strong> Fair Trade, Organic, Rainforest Alliance, and Direct Trade are the most common. Fair Trade and Organic are third-party certified and have specific standards. Direct Trade is a voluntary term with no regulatory definition, used by roasters to describe direct purchasing relationships with farms. It often implies a price premium above Fair Trade minimums but varies significantly in practice. The most transparent roasters publish what they paid for each green coffee lot.</p>

<p class="body"><strong>Tasting Notes:</strong> The most misunderstood label element. These are not flavors added to the coffee; they describe the aromatic and flavor compounds that naturally occur in the coffee when properly roasted and brewed. "Jasmine, bergamot, and peach" does not mean the coffee will taste like jasmine tea or bergamot fruit in an obvious way. It means those aromatic families are present when you pay attention. They are more of a scent vocabulary than a literal description, and experienced tasters recognize them fairly quickly with practice.</p>

